<div id="review_1975429510" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1975429510" />
    <a title="Brooke Salaz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67023306-brooke-salaz"><img alt="Brooke Salaz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1493743571p2/67023306.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1975429510?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brooke Salaz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brooke Salaz" href="/user/show/67023306-brooke-salaz">Brooke Salaz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/67023306-brooke-salaz?shelf=nyr">nyr</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1975429510" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16897026731882720971">A favorite of Samuel Johnson, rather insane look at pretty much every possible cause of this condition. Huge, repetitive, big hearted, inconsistent, Burton genuinely cares for humanity and seems to feel this work by synthesizing what the leading thinkers have said about anything even remotely related to the topic is going to help others. I particularly enjoyed the topic of love and all the artful wiles put to use by both men and women to entice and entrap the opposite sex. He comes to the conclu</span>
  <span id="freeText16897026731882720971" style="display:none">A favorite of Samuel Johnson, rather insane look at pretty much every possible cause of this condition. Huge, repetitive, big hearted, inconsistent, Burton genuinely cares for humanity and seems to feel this work by synthesizing what the leading thinkers have said about anything even remotely related to the topic is going to help others. I particularly enjoyed the topic of love and all the artful wiles put to use by both men and women to entice and entrap the opposite sex. He comes to the conclusion, as corroborated by the experts he cites, that artifice trumps nature in assigning the greater beauty. I also found quite hilarious the section on religion where he gets himself into quite a tizzy over the stupid beliefs people hold but when it comes to his own faith with zero evidence, there can be no doubt and atheism to him is the greatest foolishness there is. But even so he gives fair hearing to all the reasoning deployed by people against religion. And he rightly takes great umbrage at the role of wealth and its usurpation particularly in the Catholic religion. You can’t really get mad at him, he is so passionate and ranges so widely, getting distracted by some tangent and heading down that one for 50 pages or so. Quite a test of endurance to have gotten through it but happy I did.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16897026731882720971" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


